<br>
In the work world, he would've been fired for being disruptive. In school, he would've been expelled. In public, he probably would've been arrested. His behavior and attitude was probably just reinforced by virtue of the fact that there was no negative consequences to his guild status.<br>
<br>
As far as DoT and LoA's less than exemplary members, there aren't really any that exist. Disreputables never even make it through the screening process. Someone like Roren would've never even got past application. I can certainly speak for LoA in the year that I had been with them and I can't even recall the removal or public complaint of a single person in that time. We simply refuse to house such individuals when there are a multitude of good people to pick from. As such, we have become a tightly knit group of people, even when members have left their ranks and become alumnus or ally.<br>
<br>
Now as far as Roren and the incident...Gwaeron's Nagafen raid was May 2nd. Roren decided to send him a not so pleasant email dated May 8th and the result of that email was a rightfully outraged Gwaeron and his post. You may decide for yourself who foolishly brought something up that may have been dropped.<br>
<br>
